response:
The area of a trefoil can be calculated by finding the area of its constituent parts and subtracting the overlapping areas. The trefoil is made up of three congruent equilateral triangles with side length 2, so its total area is \(3 \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} \times 2^2 = 3\sqrt{3}\) square units. However, the trefoil also contains three identical circular sectors with radius 2 and central angle 60 degrees. The area of each sector is \(\frac{60}{360} \times \pi \times 2^2 = \frac{1}{3}\pi\) square units. Since there are three sectors, the total area removed by this process is \(\pi\) square units. Therefore, the area of the trefoil is \(3\sqrt{3} - \pi\) square units.</think>
